Assuming you have a custom `Email` data type representing email addresses and haven't provided any handling mechanisms, such as type converters or user types, for it. Let's consider an entity that uses the `Email` type:

```java
@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private Email email;

    // Getters and setters
    // ...
}
```

If you try to persist or retrieve a `User` entity using Hibernate without proper handling for the `Email` type, you may encounter an error similar to the following:

```
org.hibernate.MappingException: No Dialect mapping for JDBC type: 1111
  at org.hibernate.dialect.TypeNames.get(TypeNames.java:83)
  at org.hibernate.dialect.TypeNames.get(TypeNames.java:109)
  at org.hibernate.dialect.Dialect.getHibernateTypeName(Dialect.java:690)
  at org.hibernate.loader.custom.CustomLoader$Metadata.getHibernateType(CustomLoader.java:690)
  ...
```

This error indicates that Hibernate doesn't recognize the custom `Email` data type and doesn't know how to map it to a corresponding database type. Without a proper handling mechanism in place, Hibernate cannot persist or retrieve entities that use unsupported custom data types effectively.
